Waze / Economic Shock Test

Dan Flynn | Volpe

Overview

The goal of this quick analysis is the following:

  • Visualize Waze report data for example counties impacted by one natural disaster, in this case Hurricane Florence
  • Compare counts of total Waze incident reports for different alert types by day, by county, for 2018 and 2017

These visuals will help assess what could be drawn from the Waze alert table for to support economic activity models for the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System. Note: in addition to the alert table, additional system-generated data on jams, including spatial extent of jam and speed, are also available. These visuals only focus on the alert table, which includes user reports of crashes, weather hazards, hazards on the road, road closures, and user-reported jams.

In brief, this involved querying the Waze alert data for North Carolina, and they using GIS to assign with county FIPS codes to each alert. The data were then summarized as counts of Waze reports, by alert types, day, and county. The data were then further filtered to selected counties with varying levels of impact to Hurricane Florence, using FEMA disaster declaration. Twenty-nine counties in North Carolina were included in the disaster declaration out of the 100 counties in the state. Six states and the District of Columbia were potentially affected. Disaster was declared on September 14, 2018, and the official incident period was September 7 to 29, 2018. No disasters were declared in North Carolina in 2017.

Selected counties:

Using data from May to November of each 2017 and 2018, in total there were 6,043,010 Waze reports in NC.
